  "id": "pythagorean-theorem-visual-proof",
  "name": "Geometric Proof of the Pythagorean Theorem",
  "difficulty": "Geometry",
  "description": "<h3>Visualizing $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$</h3><p>The Pythagorean Theorem is a cornerstone of geometry, stating that in a right-angled triangle, the area of the square whose side is the hypotenuse ($c$) is equal to the sum of the areas of the squares on the other two sides ($a$ and $b$).</p><p>This visualization uses a classic <b>3-4-5 triangle</b> to demonstrate the proof:</p><ul><li><b style='color:#10b981'>Square a (Green):</b> Side length 3. Area = $3^2 = 9$.</li><li><b style='color:#3b82f6'>Square b (Blue):</b> Side length 4. Area = $4^2 = 16$.</li><li><b style='color:#6366f1'>Square c (Indigo):</b> Side length 5. Area = $5^2 = 25$.</li></ul><p>By observing the geometry, we see that $9 + 16 = 25$, confirming the relationship $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$. This property is valid for all right-angled triangles in Euclidean space.</p>",
  "tags": [
    "Geometry",
    "Visual Proof",
    "Mathematics"
  ],
